In [[Finite group|finite group theory]], an area of [[abstract algebra]], a '''strongly embedded subgroup''' of a finite group ''G'' is a [[proper subgroup]] ''H'' of even order such that ''H''&nbsp;∩&nbsp;''H''<sup>''g''</sup> has odd order whenever ''g'' is not in ''H''. 
The '''Bender–Suzuki theorem''', proved by {{harvtxt|Bender|1971}} extending work of {{harvs|txt|last=Suzuki|year1=1962|year2=1964}},  classifies the groups ''G'' with a strongly embedded subgroup ''H''. It states that either
# ''G'' has cyclic or [[Quaternion group#Generalized quaternion group|generalized quaternion Sylow 2-subgroups]] and ''H'' contains the [[centralizer]] of an [[involution (mathematics)|involution]]
# or ''G''/''O''(''G'') has a [[normal subgroup]] of odd index isomorphic to one of the [[simple group]]s PSL<sub>2</sub>(''q''), Sz(''q'') or  PSU<sub>3</sub>(''q'') where ''q''≥4  is a power of 2 and ''H'' is ''O''(''G'')N<sub>''G''</sub>(''S'') for some Sylow 2-subgroup ''S''.
{{harvtxt|Peterfalvi|2000|loc=part II}} revised Suzuki's part of the proof.

{{harvtxt|Aschbacher|1974}} extended Bender's classification to groups with a proper 2-generated core.

