In mathematical [[finite group theory]], the '''Thompson subgroup''' <math>J(P)</math> of a finite ''p''-group ''P'' refers to one of several characteristic [[subgroup]]s of ''P''. {{harvs|txt|last=Thompson|first=John G.|authorlink=John G. Thompson|year=1964}} originally defined <math>J(P)</math> to be the subgroup generated by the [[Abelian group|abelian subgroups]] of ''P'' of maximal [[Rank of a group|rank]]. More often the Thompson subgroup   <math>J(P)</math>  is defined to be the subgroup generated by the abelian subgroups of ''P'' of maximal order or the subgroup generated by the elementary abelian subgroups of ''P'' of maximal rank. In general these three subgroups can be different, though they are all called the Thompson subgroup and denoted by <math>J(P)</math>.

