In mathematical finite group theory, the '''uniqueness case''' is one of the three possibilities for groups of characteristic&nbsp;2 type given by the [[trichotomy theorem]].

The uniqueness case covers groups ''G'' of characteristic&nbsp;2 type with ''e''(''G'')&nbsp;≥&nbsp;3 that have an almost strongly ''p''-embedded maximal 2-local subgroup for all primes ''p'' whose 2-local ''p''-rank is sufficiently large (usually at least&nbsp;3).
{{harvs|txt|last=Aschbacher|year1=1983a|year2=1983b}} proved that there are no finite simple groups in the uniqueness case.

